==English==

===Etymology===
{{etyl|ang}} {{term|bryht|lang=ang}}, metathesis of {{term|beorht|lang=ang}}, from {{proto|Germanic|berhtaz}} (compare Dutch {{term|brecht|lang=nl}}, Norwegian {{term|bjart|lang=no}}), from pre-Celtic/Germanic *''bherh<sub>x</sub>gto'' (compare Welsh {{term|berth|lang=cy}} 'beautiful'), from {{proto|Indo-European|bʰereg-}} 'to gleam, whiten' (compare Middle Irish {{term|brafad|lang=mga}} 'blink of an eye', Lithuanian {{term|brekšta|lang=lt}} 'to dawn', Russian {{term||brezg}} 'dawn, daybreak', Albanian {{term|bardhë|lang=sq}} 'white', {{etyl|fa|-}} ''barâzîdan'' 'to shine', {{etyl|sa|-}} {{rfscript|Devanagari}} ''bhrájate'').

